<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-800-654  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 800 654.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 16 1989 v8 n21 p94(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Judge will hear Profs records suit. (IBM Professional OfficeSystem installed in the White House)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsGovernment AgencyRecords ManagementLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Judge Will Hear Profs Records SuitandM;A judge, not the president, most likely will decide if information on theWhite House's electronic-mail system can be erased regularly.andM;A federal judge ruled recently citizens can ask the court to consider whetherthe records stored on the White House system carry information that must bepreserved under the Presidential Records Act.andM;The decision means a group of private organizations, led by the NationalSecurity Archives in Washington, will be the first to use the act tochallenge the record-keeping practices of the president [GCN, Aug. 21].andM;Justice Department attorneys aksed the court to dismiss the case on thegrounds the judiciary had no authority in this matteer under the separationof powers doctrine.andM;Justice attorneys repeatedly have claimed the electronic notes on the WhiteHouse's IBM PC-based Professional Office System, or Profs, are the same astelephone message slips and therefore not worthy as presidential records.andO;But U.S.andP;  District Judge Charles Richey disagreed.andP;  &quot;It is not apparent as amatter of law that the challenged Profs information does not constituteagency records or presidential records,&quot; he said in his ruling.andM;The White House policy and office manuals dictate that any information onProfs to be saved as an official record must be made into hard copy.andP;  TheProfs tapes are recycled and backups are kept only for a few weeks foradministrative purposes.andM;Because the White House has established policies for saving Profs notes asrecords, the Justice attorneys also asked for summary judgment arguing thecase waged against them was arbitrary and capricious.andM;But Richey denied their motion.andM;The organizations that have challenged the destruction of the Profs notesfiled their suit after Iran-Contra investigators found many documents key tothe operation had never been transferred to hard copy.andM;Richey set a Jan. 2 deadline for motions from the two parties on how theywish to proceed with the dispute.andO;</TEXT></DOC>